---
import Base from "../../../layouts/Base.astro";
import ExampleBlock from "../../../components/ExampleBlock.astro";
import stimSampling from "../../../../examples/stim_sampling.py?raw";
import { pyQuickStartSections } from "../../../data/pyQuickStart";
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
const toc = [
  { label: "Parse and sample",  href: "#sample" },
  { label: "Measurement results", href: "#results" },
  { label: "Where to go next", href: "#next" },
];
---
<Base
  title="Python Quick Start — Stim circuits"
  current="quickstart"
  toc={toc}
  sections={pyQuickStartSections}
  currentSection="stim"
>
  <article class="shell narrow qs-page qs-page--python">
    <div class="titleblock">
      <div class="eyebrow"><a href={`${base}/quickstart/python`}>Python Quick Start</a></div>
      <h1>Stim circuits &amp; sampling</h1>
      <p class="byline">
        The most common entry point for a researcher: parse a Stim program,
        sample it many times, and look at the empirical distribution of
        measurement outcomes.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section id="sample">
      <h2>Parse and sample a Stim program</h2>
      <p>
        The snippet below prepares a GHZ-2 state and tallies the (q₀, q₁)
        outcomes over 200 shots.
      </p>
      <ExampleBlock code={stimSampling} file="docs/examples/stim_sampling.py" />
    </section>

    <section id="results">
      <h2>Loss-aware measurement results</h2>
      <p>
        Every shot is a list of <code>MeasurementResult</code> values:
        <code>ZERO</code>, <code>ONE</code>, or <code>LOST</code> when an
        atom has been lost. Loss is first-class, so you can model
        neutral-atom hardware effects without leaving the Stim flow.
      </p>
      <p>
        The mathematical background for how loss is represented internally
        — the extended five-symbol Pauli basis and the channel mappings —
        is covered in
        <a href={`${base}/quickstart/python/loss-channel`}>§ 5 Loss channel
        details</a>.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="next">
      <h2>Where to go next</h2>
      <p>
        Stim is convenient when you already have a circuit description in
        that grammar. When you'd rather build the circuit gate-by-gate from
        Python — or you need non-Clifford gates the Stim grammar can't
        express — continue to <a href={`${base}/quickstart/python/tableau`}>§
        3 Generalized Tableau</a>.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>
